<meta name="socialpost1" content="At the time of Sebold’s rape, the system was broken in Syracuse. Police brushed off rapes. Prosecutors bungled confessions. Judges overlooked irregularities. The university seemed more intent on suppressing news of a rape epidemic than solving it." />
<meta name="socialpost2" content="When Sebold was raped in May 1981, Syracuse was experiencing a rash of sexual assaults. Hers was the third such attack in the city’s Thornden Park in about seven months. Yet police had quickly consigned all of these cases to the inactive file." />
<meta name="socialpost3" content="We found a 1980 police report labeled “NO PRESS.” A former city detective testified this designation was not unusual. It meant Syracuse University had “put their foot down and said no press for any kind of rape, robbery, burglary” near the school." />
<meta name="socialpost4" content="Despite his exoneration and a sizable settlement with the state, Broadwater said the stigma of having been wrongly convicted of rape was hard to shake. “I’m still embarrassed that I was convicted and sent to prison for rape for 16 and a half years.”" />
<meta name="socialpost5" content="Some of the keys to unraveling Broadwater’s rape conviction were lying in plain sight in Sebold’s memoir, including her recollection of the botched police lineup and of the judge who broke protocol to speak to her privately during Broadwater’s trial." />
